In `calc.js` (line 7) the `divide(a, b)` helper currently divides without checking `b`, so passing in `0` or `null` from config just crashes the widget. Add a guard early on to validate inputs—for example, ensure both arguments are numbers (`Number.isFinite`) and that `b !== 0` (or truthy equivalents) before you compute the quotient. If validation fails, return an error object or `null` and let the React layer render a friendly message instead of throwing; that keeps the UI responsive while still protecting the widget.

You can still keep the same UX by bubbling validation results up through whatever UI will eventually consume `divide`. For example: 

```js
function divide(a, b) {
  if (!Number.isFinite(a) || !Number.isFinite(b)) {
    return { error: "Operands must be numbers" };
  }
  if (b === 0) {
    return { error: "Cannot divide by zero" };
  }
  return { value: a / b };
}
```

This way the consuming component (once you build the React front end) can display an inline warning instead of crashing, preserving the user experience while keeping the math helpers safe.
